In case anyone else comes by this and they don't feel like installing a commit and then falling off the upgrade path... here's a nicer crutch:

```
class ContextualAiohttpSubscriptionServer(AiohttpSubscriptionServer):
    def __init__(self, schema, keep_alive=True, loop=None):
        super().__init__(schema, keep_alive, loop)
        self._check_updated()

    @staticmethod
    def _check_updated():
        import pkg_resources
        import warnings
        from distutils.version import StrictVersion
        graphql_ws_dist = pkg_resources.get_distribution('graphql_ws')
        # https://github.com/graphql-python/graphql-ws/issues/7
        if StrictVersion(graphql_ws_dist.version) > '0.2.0':
            warnings.warn('`graphql_ws` is upgraded, check for `execute` fix')
            import sys; sys.exit() # optional, terminate immediately!

    def execute(self, request_context, params):
        # https://github.com/graphql-python/graphql-ws/issues/7
        params['context_value'] = request_context
        return super().execute(request_context, params)
```

It'll yell at you when `graphql_ws` gets upgraded past 0.2.0 so you can (maybe) upgrade then.

Embedding python is actually trivial. Here is an example using your `add.cc` file:

```
#include <Python.h>

// The preprocessor defined initializer for our example module.
extern "C" PyObject *initexample();

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
  Py_Initialize();
  PyObject* main_module = PyImport_AddModule("__main__");
  PyObject* main_dict = PyModule_GetDict(main_module);

  // Initialize our external module
  initexample();

  // We can now import our example module just like any other module.
  PyRun_StringFlags("import example\n"
                    "\n"
                    "print example.add(3,2);\n"
                    , Py_file_input, main_dict, main_dict, NULL);

  Py_Finalize();
  exit(0);
}

```

To compile do:
```

g++ -o hello-pybind11.o -c -g -Wall -std=c++14 -I/usr/include/python2.7 -I/usr/local/include hello-pybind11.cc
g++ -o add.o -c -g -Wall -std=c++14 -I/usr/include/python2.7 -I/usr/local/include add.cc
g++ -o hello-pybind11 hello-pybind11.o add.o -lpython2.7

```

But what got me stuck is how to create a binding for a C++ singleton.

I got curious also, since I may be interested in this in the future.

It looks like the importing is different in python3 than python2. In python3, you have to use `PyImport_AppendInittab` to register the init function for the module, and the import machinery will use the given info.

Unfortunately, it requires a C function pointer that returns a `PyObject *` for the module, which isn't really compatible with C++. You need a plain C function (not a class member function, not `std::bind`, etc) that takes no arguments and will return the new module. Since it takes no arguments (that could be used to differentiate between different modules), you are basically restricted to hard-coding it yourself for each module.

This is the best I can think of. There are probably other ways, but I'm not too familiar with python internals.

    #include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
    namespace py = pybind11;

    const char * world() { return "Hello world!"; }

    // Looks a lot like a normal pybind11 export function...
    PyObject * InitHello(void)
    {
        py::module m("hello", "my hello world Python module with pybind11");
        m.def("world", &world);

        // Not positive if incrementing is required
        return m.ptr();
    }

    int main(int argc, char ** argv)
    {
        PyImport_AppendInittab("hello", &InitHello);
        Py_Initialize();
        PyRun_SimpleString("import hello\nprint( hello.world() )");
        Py_Finalize();
    
        return 0;
    }

See: https://docs.python.org/3/c-api/import.html#c.PyImport_AppendInittab and http://bugs.python.org/issue4592

